Backend specification for Directus repo
Context: poppim-web frontend is waiting on these changes. All field names below must match exactly — the frontend will reference them verbatim. Backend repo: u2giants/directus.
1. Schema changes (pm-system/apply-schema.mjs or equivalent)
1a. New fields on the product collection
Add all eight fields below. All are string | null, read-only in the UI (they're managed by sync scripts, not by users). Add them in this order so they group sensibly in Data Studio.
// ClickUp hierarchy — space > folder > list
{ field: 'clickup_space_id',    type: 'string', schema: { is_nullable: true }, meta: { readonly: true, group: null } },
{ field: 'clickup_space_name',  type: 'string', schema: { is_nullable: true }, meta: { readonly: true } },
{ field: 'clickup_folder_id',   type: 'string', schema: { is_nullable: true }, meta: { readonly: true } },
{ field: 'clickup_folder_name', type: 'string', schema: { is_nullable: true }, meta: { readonly: true } },
{ field: 'clickup_list_id',     type: 'string', schema: { is_nullable: true }, meta: { readonly: true } },
// Task metadata not currently imported
{ field: 'clickup_creator_id',       type: 'string', schema: { is_nullable: true }, meta: { readonly: true } },
{ field: 'clickup_creator_name',     type: 'string', schema: { is_nullable: true }, meta: { readonly: true } },
{ field: 'clickup_time_estimate_ms', type: 'bigInteger', schema: { is_nullable: true }, meta: { readonly: true } },
{ field: 'clickup_orderindex',       type: 'string', schema: { is_nullable: true }, meta: { readonly: true } },
Why clickup_orderindex as string: ClickUp returns it as a decimal string like "5.00000000000000000000000000000000" — 32 decimal places, exceeds float64 precision. Store as text; sort by casting to NUMERIC at query time.
Why clickup_creator_* as two fields: ClickUp users aren't necessarily in our Directus instance. Storing both id and name preserves the identity without requiring a join.
Why NOT clickup_description_html: The existing product.description field stores ClickUp's text_content (plain text). Adding the HTML version would require either changing that field's type to text (long) — if it isn't already — or adding a new description_html field. If the current description field is varchar(255) or similar, it needs to be changed to text (unlimited) before re-importing descriptions; many ClickUp task descriptions are longer than 255 characters. Check the current column type and widen it to text if needed. Do not create a separate description_html field — store the HTML in description directly and have the frontend handle rendering it safely. Update the sync to write task.description (the HTML) instead of task.text_content (the plain text strip).
2. Backfill migration (pm-system/migration/backfill-clickup-hierarchy.mjs)
Phase A: Build the hierarchy map from ClickUp
Call these ClickUp API v2 endpoints (3–5 total API calls regardless of product count):
GET /api/v2/team                                      → get team_id
GET /api/v2/team/{team_id}/space?archived=false       → all spaces [{id, name}, ...]
For each space:
  GET /api/v2/space/{space_id}/folder?archived=false  → folders with nested lists
  GET /api/v2/space/{space_id}/list?archived=false    → folderless lists in this space
The folder response shape:
{
  "folders": [
    {
      "id": "90123456789",
      "name": "Design Management",
      "lists": [
        { "id": "901234567890", "name": "Licensing Management" },
        { "id": "901234567891", "name": "Sourcing/Sampling Projects" }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
The folderless-list response shape:
{
  "lists": [
    { "id": "901234560001", "name": "Newsletter Whiteboard" }
  ]
}
Build this lookup structure in memory:
// Map from list_id → full location context
const byListId = new Map()
// Map from list_name → Set of list_ids (to detect ambiguity)
const byListName = new Map()
for (const space of spaces) {
  for (const folder of space.folders) {
    for (const list of folder.lists) {
      byListId.set(list.id, {
        list_id: list.id,
        list_name: list.name,
        folder_id: folder.id,
        folder_name: folder.name,
        space_id: space.id,
        space_name: space.name,
      })
      if (!byListName.has(list.name)) byListName.set(list.name, new Set())
      byListName.get(list.name).add(list.id)
    }
  }
  for (const list of space.folderlesslists) {
    byListId.set(list.id, {
      list_id: list.id,
      list_name: list.name,
      folder_id: null,
      folder_name: null,     // folderless: folder fields are null
      space_id: space.id,
      space_name: space.name,
    })
    if (!byListName.has(list.name)) byListName.set(list.name, new Set())
    byListName.get(list.name).add(list.id)
  }
}
Phase B: Resolve products
Query Directus for all products that have a clickup_list_name set:
const products = await directus.request(
  readItems('product', {
    fields: ['id', 'clickup_list_name', 'clickup_url'],
    filter: { clickup_list_name: { _nnull: true } },
    limit: -1,
  })
)
For each product, resolve its hierarchy location:
const nameIds = byListName.get(product.clickup_list_name)
if (nameIds?.size === 1) {
  // Unique name → resolve directly from map, no API call needed
  const loc = byListId.get([...nameIds][0])
  // → update product with loc.*

} else if (nameIds?.size > 1) {
  // Ambiguous name → must call the task endpoint to get list.id
  const taskId = extractTaskId(product.clickup_url)  // last path segment
  const task = await clickup.get(`/task/${taskId}`)
  const loc = byListId.get(task.list.id)
  // → update product with loc.*

} else {
  // clickup_list_name set but no matching list in current workspace tree
  // Log as warning — list may have been deleted or archived
}
extractTaskId(url) implementation:
// ClickUp task URLs are either:
//   https://app.clickup.com/t/{task_id}
//   https://app.clickup.com/t/{workspace_id}/{task_id}
function extractTaskId(url) {
  if (!url) return null
  const parts = url.split('/').filter(Boolean)
  return parts[parts.length - 1]  // always the last segment
}
Phase C: Write back to Directus
Batch the updates — don't send 17,859 individual PATCH requests. Group by list_name (since products in the same list get identical hierarchy values), then run one updateItems call per unique list:
// Group products by resolved list_id
const groups = new Map()  // list_id → { loc, productIds[] }
for (const { productId, loc } of resolved) {
  if (!groups.has(loc.list_id)) groups.set(loc.list_id, { loc, ids: [] })
  groups.get(loc.list_id).ids.push(productId)
}
// One update call per list — typically 10–30 lists, not 17,859 individual PATCHes
for (const { loc, ids } of groups.values()) {
  await directus.request(
    updateItems('product', ids, {
      clickup_list_id:     loc.list_id,
      clickup_folder_id:   loc.folder_id,
      clickup_folder_name: loc.folder_name,
      clickup_space_id:    loc.space_id,
      clickup_space_name:  loc.space_name,
    })
  )
  console.log(`Updated ${ids.length} products → ${loc.space_name} / ${loc.folder_name ?? '(no folder)'} / ${loc.list_name}`)
}
Expected result: ~10–30 batch updates covering all 17,859 products in a few seconds.
3. Update the ongoing ClickUp sync
In the existing import script (pm-system/migration/clickup-work-import.mjs or wherever tasks are upserted into the product collection), add these fields to every task upsert:
The ClickUp GET /list/{list_id}/task (and individual GET /task/{task_id}) response includes:
{
  "list":   { "id": "901234567890", "name": "Licensing Management" },
  "folder": { "id": "90123456789",  "name": "Design Management", "hidden": false },
  "space":  { "id": "90123000000" },
  "creator": { "id": 1234567, "username": "albert", "email": "albert@pop.com", "profilePicture": "..." },
  "time_estimate": 3600000,
  "orderindex": "5.00000000000000000000000000000000"
}
Note: space only returns id on task objects, not name. Maintain the space-name map from the hierarchy tree built in Phase A above, and look up the name by ID.
Add to the upsert payload:
{
  // existing fields...
  // hierarchy
  clickup_list_id:     task.list?.id ?? null,
  clickup_folder_id:   task.folder?.id ?? null,
  clickup_folder_name: task.folder?.name ?? null,
  clickup_space_id:    task.space?.id ?? null,
  clickup_space_name:  spaceNameMap.get(task.space?.id) ?? null,  // from pre-built map
  // new task metadata
  clickup_creator_id:       String(task.creator?.id ?? '') || null,
  clickup_creator_name:     task.creator?.username ?? null,
  clickup_time_estimate_ms: task.time_estimate ?? null,
  clickup_orderindex:       task.orderindex ?? null,
}
If the folder is hidden or the list is folderless, task.folder may return { id: "...", name: "...", hidden: true } — still store it. If the task has no folder (folderless list), folder.hidden will be true and folder.name will be something like "hidden" — in that case set both clickup_folder_id and clickup_folder_name to null.
4. Also run the creator/time_estimate/orderindex backfill
The hierarchy map approach above gets hierarchy from the tree without touching individual tasks. To backfill clickup_creator_id, clickup_creator_name, clickup_time_estimate_ms, and clickup_orderindex you need the per-task response — these fields aren't in the list/folder tree.
Two options:
Option A (preferred): Extend the hierarchy backfill script to also call individual tasks. For most lists, you can call GET /list/{list_id}/task?include_closed=false&subtasks=false to get all tasks in a list in one call (paginated). This is more efficient than per-task calls:
For each list in the hierarchy map (typically 10–30 lists):
  GET /api/v2/list/{list_id}/task?include_closed=false&subtasks=false&page=0
  → returns tasks[] each with creator, time_estimate, orderindex
  Paginate until page is empty (ClickUp returns 100 per page)
  For each task: match on task.id to find the product, then update those 4 fields
Rate limit: 100 req/min. At 100 tasks/request, 17,859 tasks = ~179 pages across all lists. At 100 req/min that's under 2 minutes. Build in a 600ms sleep between requests to stay safe.
Option B (simpler but slower): For each product with a clickup_url, extract the task ID and call GET /task/{task_id}. At 100 req/min with 17,859 products = ~3 hours. Not recommended.
Use Option A.
5. Directus access policy
Once the new fields exist, confirm the pm_user role (whatever role logged-in Poppim users get) has read access to all new fields on product. The frontend will request them explicitly by name in the fields parameter of readItems calls — if the role doesn't grant read access to a field, Directus silently omits it rather than returning an error, which would look like empty data.
6. Verification checklist
After running the schema migration and backfill script, confirm these in Directus Data Studio before notifying the frontend:
Field presence: Go to Settings → Data Model → product. Confirm all 9 new fields appear: clickup_space_id, clickup_space_name, clickup_folder_id, clickup_folder_name, clickup_list_id, clickup_creator_id, clickup_creator_name, clickup_time_estimate_ms, clickup_orderindex.
Coverage: Run this SQL on the Postgres database:
SELECT
  COUNT(*) AS total,
  COUNT(clickup_space_name) AS has_space,
  COUNT(clickup_folder_name) AS has_folder,
  COUNT(clickup_list_id) AS has_list_id,
  COUNT(clickup_creator_name) AS has_creator,
  COUNT(clickup_time_estimate_ms) AS has_time_estimate
FROM product
WHERE clickup_list_name IS NOT NULL;
Expected: has_space and has_list_id should equal total (every product with a list name gets a space and list_id). has_folder will be slightly less if some lists are folderless. has_creator and has_time_estimate will be whatever ClickUp returns (time_estimate may be 0 for tasks that don't have one set).
Spot check: Pull a known product in Data Studio — e.g. one from "Licensing Management" — and confirm its fields show clickup_space_name = "POP Creations", clickup_folder_name = "Design Management", clickup_list_id is a valid ClickUp ID string.
Hierarchy distribution: Run this to confirm the space split looks right:
SELECT clickup_space_name, clickup_folder_name, clickup_list_name, COUNT(*)
FROM product
WHERE clickup_list_name IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY 1, 2, 3
ORDER BY 1, 2, 3;
This output is the exact hierarchy tree as Poppim will navigate it — share it with the frontend team once confirmed.
description field length: Run:
SELECT MAX(LENGTH(description)) FROM product;
If result > 255, confirm the column is TEXT not VARCHAR(255). If it's varchar, widen it before re-importing HTML descriptions.
7. What the frontend picks up immediately (no further coordination needed)
Once steps 1–6 are done, the frontend changes are entirely in this repo. The frontend will:
Add the 9 new fields to src/lib/types.ts
Add clickup_folder_name, clickup_space_name, clickup_list_id to the fields fetched in PRODUCT_SUMMARY_FIELDS
Surface them as group-by / filter options in the pipeline
Show the space / folder / list breadcrumb on cards and in the modal
No further backend changes are needed after this schema + backfill work is done.
Summary of deliverables from backend
#	Deliverable	Expected time
1	9 new fields added to product schema	30 min
2	backfill-clickup-hierarchy.mjs run in production	1–2 hours to write + ~5 min to run
3	Creator/time_estimate/orderindex backfilled via per-list task calls	same script, ~3 min to run
4	Ongoing sync updated to write all new fields	1 hour
5	description column widened to TEXT if needed	15 min
6	Verification SQL output shared with frontend	15 min
